<TITLE> Ctg, Sylhet report first swine flu cases </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Sylhet, Sept 1 (bdnews24.com)  An air force officer and a doctor are the first confirmed swine flu cases in Chittagong and Sylhet. An air force officer Flight Lieutenant Tanvirul Islam is under treatment in Chittagong air force hospital, a doctor of the hospital said. IEDCR tests confirmed the H1N1 virus on Tuesday. "Tanvirul was admitted last Sunday. Observing swine flu like symptoms doctors sent a blood sample for test to IEDCR in Dhaka. The result came back today," said the doctor, who wished not to be named. Family members said Tanvirul had just returned from Malaysia on August 30 after attending a month-long training programme. The first case of swine flu was detected in Sylhet on Monday, said Najmul Islam, principal of Ragib Rabeya Medical College Hospital. Islam said Mohammad Idris Ali, 30, a medical officer of the hospital's Paediatric Department, tested positive for swine flu after samples were sent to IEDCR in Dhaka. He said Ali was being treated at his home. The two cases surfaced as the number of IEDCR's confirmed cases rose to 247, with 34 new cases detected on Tuesday. Meanwhile, authorities in Sylhet said they had taken preventive measures to check spread of the virus in the area. "All sorts of preventive measures are in place," civil surgeon in Sylhet Dr Faiz Ahmed told bdnews24.com. He said awareness was the key to preventing the spread of swine flu virus. Dr Mohammad Ishteshamul Haque Dulal, assistant director of Sylhet MAG Osmani Medical College Hospital, said they were making extra arrangement to accommodate such patients. A 15-strong committee has been monitoring patients who come to see doctors at the public hospital with flu symptoms. Another three-member expert team of the hospital is checking incoming patients on international flights at Osmani International Airport, the officials said. bdnews24.com/c
